On Escalation Ticket # 00420313 the new comment has been added: Robert-Zoltan Sumi:

@WaitingOnEngineer According to the 6th September log there was a communication problem: the client received a certificate from the server, but in the subsequent steps the server did not acknowledged it. This is probably a server issue. The second, 10th September log shows that the client is communicating with the server, but there is no DPI certificate.

Regarding the client versions, they seem to be OK. One of the log file starts with 3.0.2.1007, the corresponding screenshot also shows 3.0.2.1007. The other log reports version 3.0.1.2002, the screenshot also shows 3.0.1.2002.

On Escalation Ticket # 00420313 the new comment has been added: Alexandra-Alina Pascalau:

Hi,



It is very difficult to follow the issue and the attachments in this case , so please make a new test on one of the affected computers.

Please check that the firewall is not blocking the communication of that computer with the server.
 
 telnet <IP> <PORT>

Also, for testing purposes, please disable the DPI certificate for the computer that you are testing with.

Follow these steps:

1. Enable registration logs:
     

--- CODE ---
    vim /EPPServer/sieratool/webservicefree/webservice.php
--- CODE ---

    set DEBUG to true and DEBUG_VERBOSITY to 1011 and save the file

   2. Reregister the machine:


--- CODE ---
        select id from clientmachine where name = 'machine_name';
--- CODE ---

                                  - this will provide the machine_id


--- CODE ---
        UPDATE license SET assigned_to = null where assigned_to = machine_id;
        UPDATE clientmachine SET trialversion = NULL, reregister = 1 WHERE id = machine_id;
        DELETE FROM certificate WHERE assigned_to = machine_id;
--- CODE ---

      3.  Update Policies

       4. Provide the logs from /EPPServer/sieratool/log/WebServiceFree.log

       5.  Very important: Disable the debug from point 1


        6. Collect  client logs during this test.

    Please let us know if there are multiple computers that are affected by this issue.

Thank you,
Alina

@WaitingOnEngineer
